'''Pedro Leitão Brito''' ({{IPA|pt|ˈpe.dɾu lej.ˈtɐ̃w ˈbɾi.tu|lang}}; born 6 January 1970), commonly known as '''Bubista''' ({{IPA|kea|bu.ˈbis.tɐ|lang}}), is a Cape Verdean [[manager (association football)|football manager]] and former [[football player|player]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|centre-back]]. He is the manager of the [[Cape Verde national football team|Cape Verde national team]].

On 13 October 2025, he led Cape Verde to its [[2026 FIFA World Cup|first ever FIFA World Cup]].

==Club career==
In 1995, Bubista joined Spanish [[Segunda División]] club [[CD Badajoz|Badajoz]], making two league appearances in his single season at the club. In 1997, Bubista joined Angolan club [[Atlético Sport Aviação|ASA]]. Bubista played for ASA for six seasons, before returning to his native Cape Verde, joining [[:pt:Clube Desportivo Falcões do Norte|Falcões do Norte]] in 2003.<ref name = "NFT">{{NFT player|id=1313|accessdate=25 September 2020}}</ref>

==International career==
In 1991, Bubista made his debut for [[Cape Verde national football team|Cape Verde]].<ref name = "NFT"/> Bubista later captained the country, making 28 appearances for Cape Verde during his career.<ref name = "Portugal">{{cite web|url=https://portugalinews.eu/bubista-is-the-new-leader-of-the-cape-verdean-national-football-team/|title=Bubista is the new leader of the Cape Verdean national football team|publisher=portugalinews|date=29 January 2020|accessdate=25 September 2020}}</ref>

==Managerial career==
Following his playing career, Bubista managed domestic Cape Verdean clubs [[CS Mindelense|Mindelense]], [[Académica do Mindelo]], [[Sporting Clube da Praia|Sporting Praia]] and [[Batuque FC|Batuque]]. In January 2020, he was named manager of Cape Verde.<ref name = "Portugal"/> He managed his nation to qualification for the [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations]] after a 1–0 away victory over [[Mozambique national football team|Mozambique]] on the final matchday.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/match/_/gameId/596245/cape-verde-islands-mozambique |title=Mozambique 0–1 Cape Verde Islands |publisher=ESPN |date=31 March 2021 }}</ref> He later guided the team to the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/sports/soccer/profile-cape-verde-islands-team-2023-africa-cup-nations-2024-01-08/ |title=Profile of Cape Verde Islands team for 2023 Africa Cup of Nations |publisher=Reuters |date=8 January 2024 }}</ref> where they advanced to the quarterfinals.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cafonline.com/afcon2025/news/mendes-penalty-sends-cape-verde-into-quarter-finals/ |title=Mendes penalty sends Cape Verde into quarter-finals |publisher=CAF Online |date=29 January 2024 }}</ref>

On 13 October 2025, he led Cape Verde to its [[2026 FIFA World Cup|first ever FIFA World Cup]] after a 3–0 home win against [[Eswatini national football team|Eswatini]]. Doing so, Cape Verde became the second-smallest nation ever to reach the [[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]] after [[Iceland national football team|Iceland]] did it in [[2018 FIFA World Cup|2018]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c04q0gd0yedo|title=Cape Verde become second-smallest nation to reach World Cup|publisher=BBC|date=13 October 2025|accessdate=13 October 2025}}</ref> He was subsequently named the [[CAF Awards|CAF Coach of the Year]] for 2025, at the CAF Awards 2025.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Achraf Hakimi, Ghizlane Chebbak lead Morocco’s Golden Night at CAF Awards 2025|url=https://www.cafonline.com/news/achraf-hakimi-ghizlane-chebbak-lead-morocco-s-golden-night-at-caf-awards-2025/|website=Confederation of African Football|access-date=1 December 2025|language=|date=19 November 2025}}</ref><ref name=":0" />

